DOM-Based HTML Injection
User input is inserted into the HTML Document Object Model (DOM) without sufficient encoding. Consequently, web browsers interpret certain symbols as control characters and not as text.

The following functionality manipulates the DOM in a way that results in unescaped HTML code being interpreted by the browser:
{{
- foo
- bar
}}
This makes the application vulnerable to HTML injection, and potentially also to cross-site scripting (XSS). An adversary could embed HTML or JavaScript code into the web application, which is respectively interpreted or executed in the browser of the victim.

